  "prompt": "If light does not have mass, then how can it bend due to gravity? How can light have momentum if mass is 0?",
  "response": "Light, despite being massless, can bend due to gravity and carry momentum because gravity and momentum in physics don't solely depend on mass. Here's an explanation:\n\n### 1. **Why Light Bends Due to Gravity (General Relativity)**\n   - According to Einstein's theory of **General Relativity**, gravity is not just a force between masses but rather the curvature of **spacetime** caused by mass and energy.\n   - Light travels along the shortest path in spacetime, called a **geodesic**. When spacetime is curved by a massive object (like a star or black hole), the path of light also curves, even though light has no mass.\n   - This phenomenon is called **gravitational lensing** and has been observed experimentally, confirming Einstein\u2019s predictions.\n\n### 2. **Why Light Has Momentum (Quantum Mechanics and Electromagnetism)**\n   - Light is made up of photons, which are massless particles. \n   - In **quantum mechanics** and **electrodynamics**, photons carry **momentum** even though they have no mass. This momentum is related to their **energy** and **frequency** via the equation:\n     \\[\n     p = \\frac{E}{c}\n     \\]\n     where \\( p \\) is the momentum, \\( E \\) is the energy of the photon, and \\( c \\) is the speed of light.\n   - The energy of a photon is determined by its frequency (\\( E = hf \\), where \\( h \\) is Planck's constant and \\( f \\) is the frequency).\n   - This momentum can be observed in phenomena like the **radiation pressure** of light, where photons transfer momentum to objects they strike.\n\n### Key Takeaways:\n   - Light bends due to gravity because gravity warps spacetime, and light follows the curvature of spacetime.\n   - Light carries momentum because momentum is not solely dependent on mass; it is also tied to energy and frequency, which photons possess.\n\nThese ideas, rooted in both General Relativity and Quantum Mechanics, explain how light, despite being massless, interacts with gravity and carries momentum.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
